  <refnamediv>
    <refname>gqpe-interpolate-gps</refname>
    <refpurpose>Interpolate GPS coordinates</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>

  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>gqpe-interpolate-gps</command>
      <arg choice="opt" rep="repeat">OPTION</arg>
      <arg choice="opt">DIRNAME</arg>
      <arg choice="opt" rep="repeat">FILENAME</arg>
    </cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>

  <refsect1>

    <title>Description</title>

    <para><command>gqpe-interpolate-gps</command> is a command line tool to
    interpolate GPS coordinates in a timed range of image files.</para>

    <para><command>gqpe-interpolate-gps</command> has two modes: The first one
    receives a directory, and it automatically interpolates the GPS coordinates
    of all photographs without GPS data, sorted by timestamp, such as they are
    between two photographs, <varname>P</varname> and <varname>Q</varname>,
    where both <varname>P</varname> and <varname>Q</varname> have GPS data and
    the distance between <varname>P</varname> and <varname>Q</varname> is less
    than 1,000 meters, and the time between <varname>P</varname> and
    <varname>Q</varname> is less than one day.</para>

    <para>The second mode uses the <option>-r</option> option, and receives a
    set of photographs. The first and last one (time wise) must have GPS data,
    and then the photographs in between have their GPS coordinates
    interpolated.</para>

    <para>The interpolation is a naive one, treating the latitude and longitude
    as planar coordinates instead of polar coordinates; this works reasonably
    well for small distances, but it does not for large ones.</para>

  </refsect1>

  <refsect1>

    <title>Options</title>

    <para>The following options are accepted.</para>

    <variablelist>

      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-h</option></term>
        <term><option>--help</option></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Show help options.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>

      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-r</option></term>
        <term><option>--range</option></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Use a range of photographs.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>

      <varlistentry>
        <term><option>-v</option></term>
        <term><option>--verbose</option></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Be verbose.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>

    </variablelist>

  </refsect1>

